{"title_page": "McVitie's", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = McVitie's\n| native_name      = <!-- Company's name in home country language -->\n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-2 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. If there is more than one native name, in different languages, enter those names using {{tl|lang}}, instead. -->\n| trading_name     = <!-- d/b/a/, doing business as - if different from legal name above -->\n| logo             = New McVitie's Logo.jpg\n| logo_size        = 220px\n| logo_caption     = The McVitie's logo as updated in 2005\n| image            = \n| image_caption    = \n| type             = Subsidiary\n| traded_as        = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| founder          = Richard McVitie\n| defunct          = <!-- {{End date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| fate             = \n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = \n| industry         = [[Confectionery]]\n| genre            = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies -->\n| products         = \n| production       = \n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| aum              = <!-- Only used with financial services companies -->\n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = [[pladis]]\n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = {{URL|www.mcvities.com}}\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n| romanized        = \n| former type      = \n| foundation       = [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]] ({{Start date|1830}})\n| location_city    = \n| location_country = [[United Kingdom]]\n| locations        = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices, etc. -->\n| bodystyle        = \n}}\n\n'''McVitie's''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] snack food brand owned by [[United Biscuits]]. The name derives from the original Scottish biscuit maker, McVitie & Price, Ltd., established in 1830 on Rose Street in [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]]. The company moved to various sites in the city before completing the St. Andrews Biscuit Works factory on Robertson Avenue in the [[Gorgie]] district in 1888.<ref name=\"archives\">{{Cite web|last=The National Archives of Scotland |authorlink=National Archives of Scotland |title=McVitie & Price, Ltd |url=http://www.dswebhosting.info/NAS/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Site20&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqSearch=(RefNo=='GD381/3') |accessdate=2 November 2007 |format=&ndash; <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=author%3AThe+National+Archives+of+Scotland+intitle%3AMcVitie+%26+Price%2C+Ltd&as_publication=&as_ylo=&as_yhi=&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup>  }}{{dead link|date=December 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The company also established one in Glasgow and two large manufacturing plants south of the border, in [[Heaton Chapel]], [[Stockport]], and [[Harlesden]], [[London]]. Under United Biscuits McVitie's holds a [[Royal Warrant of Appointment (United Kingdom)|Royal Warrant]] from Queen [[Elizabeth II]].\n\nThe best-selling [[biscuit]] manufacturer in the United Kingdom, McVitie's produces [[chocolate digestive]]s, [[Hobnob biscuit|Hobnobs]] and [[Rich tea]] (ranked the three favourite biscuits to [[Dunking (biscuit)|dunk]] into tea), and [[Jaffa Cakes]] (the best selling cake in the IDK).\n\n==History==\n[[File:McVitie's Biscuit Factory, Wellington Road North, Stockport - geograph.org.uk - 803875.jpg|thumb|McVitie's factory in [[Manchester]] and [[Stockport]] which produces over 2,000 [[Jaffa Cakes]] a minute.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Jaffa Cakes - definitely not biscuits - prepare to take on imitators |last=Wallop |first=Harry |quote=The factory, which covers more than 10 acres, produces 2,000 Jaffa Cakes a minute |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=6 May 2012 }}</ref>]]\nRobert McVitie had two biscuit works at the head of [[Leith Walk]] in [[Edinburgh]] in 1870: 12 Antigua Street and 2 East London Street. McVitie lived nearby in a flat at 76 Broughton Street.<ref>Edinburgh Post Office Directory 1870</ref>\n\nThe established Edinburgh biscuit company of Robert McVitie was joined in 1875 by [[Charles Edward Price]] to create McVitie & Price. On the death of Robert senior, Robert McVitie junior joined and the firm expanded. In 1888 they built the huge St Andrews Biscuit Works on Robertson Avenue in the [[Gorgie]] district of south-west Edinburgh.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.mcvities.co.uk/about | title=McVitie's History &#124; McVitie's UK}}</ref>\n\nThough the original Gorgie factory burned down in 1894, it was rebuilt the same year and remained operative until 1969, when production ceased and operations were transferred to the English sites which had been established at [[Harlesden]] in 1910 and [[Manchester]] in 1917. The firm acquired the Edinburgh bakery of Simon Henderson & Sons in 1922.<ref name=\"archives\"/> McVitie & Price merged with another Scottish bakery company, Macfarlane, Lang & Co., Ltd, in 1948 to become United Biscuits Group.<ref>{{Cite web | last=United Biscuits| title=Our History| url=http://www.unitedbiscuits.com/802561A0047922E/vWeb/pcTSTT5DWHZ4| accessdate=6 November 2007 | format= &ndash; <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=author%3AUnited+Biscuits+intitle%3AOur+History&as_publication=&as_ylo=&as_yhi=&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup> | postscript=<!--None-->}} {{Dead link|date=March 2009}}</ref> McVitie's brand products are now manufactured in five United Kingdom factories: the two former McVitie & Price factories in Harlesden and Manchester, a former Macfarlane, Lang & Co. factory named Victoria Biscuit Works in [[Glasgow]], a former [[Carr's]] factory named The Biscuit Works established 1831 in [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]], and the McVitie's Cake Co. factory (formerly Riley's Toffee Works) in [[Halifax, West Yorkshire|Halifax]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.unitedbiscuits.com/80256C1A0047922E/vWeb/pcTSTT5DWHZ7| title=Our Locations| publisher=United Biscuits| accessdate=16 August 2007| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070624214113/http://www.unitedbiscuits.com/80256C1A0047922E/vWeb/pcTSTT5DWHZ7| archivedate = 24 June 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:McVitie's chocolate digestive biscuit.jpg|thumb|200px|left|McVitie's [[chocolate digestive]]. First produced in 1925, travel writer [[Bill Bryson]] called it a \u201cBritish masterpiece\u201d. It is the most popular biscuit in the UK to [[Dunking (biscuit)|dunk]] into tea.]]\n\nMcVitie & Price's first major biscuit was the McVitie's [[digestive biscuit|Digestive]], created in 1892 by a new young employee at the company named [[Sir Alexander Grant, 1st Baronet|Alexander Grant]].<ref name=\"McVities\"/> The biscuit was given its name because it was thought that its high baking soda content served as an aid to food digestion.<ref name=\"McVities\">[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2591803/McVities-Digestive-Hobnobs-shock-Weve-eating-wrong-way.html \"Crumbs, we've been eating McVitie's Digestives and Hobnobs all wrong! Firm says chocolate part is the BOTTOM\"]. ''Daily Mail'' (London). Retrieved 28 December 2014</ref> Grant was later to become managing director of the company. In 1923 he was the main benefactor in the establishing the [[National Library of Scotland]] giving an endowment of \u00a3100,000. Grant donated a further \u00a3100,000 in 1928 to assist with the building of the [[National Library of Scotland|National Library]] premises on [[George IV Bridge]] in Edinburgh.<ref>Macmillan, p.238-52</ref>\n\nIn 1924 Ramsay MacDonald, prime minister of Britain\u2019s new Labour Government, admitted that Grant had given him a Daimler car and \u00a330 000 of shares in the McVitie and Price company. Grant had been MacDonald\u2019s childhood friend, and shortly after received a baronetcy (hereditary knighthood) from the prime minister. The affair, regarded by many as corruption by the prime minister, severely shook the government.<ref>William D Rubinstein 'Twentieth-Century Britain: A Political History', Palgrave, 2003 p146.</ref>\n\nThe McVitie's Chocolate Homewheat Digestive was created in 1925. Over 71 million packets of McVitie's [[chocolate digestive]]s are eaten in the United Kingdom each year, equating to 52 biscuits per second.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.unitedbiscuits.com/80256C1A0047922E/vWeb/pcTSTT5EPGEC| title=McVitie's| publisher=United Biscuits| accessdate=16 August 2007| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070809043301/http://www.unitedbiscuits.com/80256C1A0047922E/vWeb/pcTSTT5EPGEC| archivedate = 9 August 2007}}</ref> [[HobNob]]s were launched in 1985 and a [[Types of chocolate|milk chocolate]] variant followed in 1987.<ref name=\"McVities\"/> Launched in 1927, [[Jaffa Cakes]]  were ranked the best selling cake or biscuit in the UK in 2012.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/9249366/Jaffa-Cakes-definitely-not-biscuits-prepare-to-take-on-imitators.html \"Jaffa Cakes - definitely not biscuits - prepare to take on imitators\"]. ''The Daily Telegraph'' (London). Retrieved 28 December 2014</ref>\n\nIn 1947, McVitie & Price made the wedding cake for [[Elizabeth II|Princess Elizabeth]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Philip Mountbatten]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7100546.stm| title=Sixty facts about a royal marriage (item 43)| publisher=BBC News| accessdate=15 January 2008 | date=18 November 2007}}</ref> Some of the products in the McVitie's line were rebranded ''McV'' in 2002, but this was replaced in 2005 with a restyled version of the ''McVitie's'' brand logo. In 2007, United Biscuits [[licensed]] the McVitie's brand to [[Meiji Seika|Meiji Seika Kaisha Ltd]] for biscuit production in [[Japan]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nicecupofteaandasitdown.com/biscuits/previous.php3?item=157| title=Japanese McVities Digestives| publisher=nicecupofteaandasitdown.com| accessdate=16 August 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:McVitie's HobNobs Nobbly Oaty Biscuits.jpg|thumb|right|McVitie's [[Hobnob biscuit|Hobnobs]] (plain). The chocolate version was named the UK's favourite biscuit in a 2014 poll.]]\nIn 2009, McVitie's biscuits were voted the most popular biscuits to [[Dunking (biscuit)|dunk]] in [[Tea in the United Kingdom|tea]], with McVitie's [[chocolate digestive]]s, [[Rich tea]] and [[Hobnobs]] ranked the country's top three favourite biscuits in 2009.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/foodanddrink/foodanddrinknews/4927255/Chocolate-digestive-is-nations-favourite-dunking-biscuit.html \"Chocolate digestive is nation's favourite dunking biscuit\"]. ''The Daily Telegraph'' (London). 2 May 2009</ref>\n\nIn March 2011, it was announced that [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|Prince William]] had chosen a [[groom's cake]] for his [[Wedding of Prince William and Catherine Middleton|wedding]] reception, made from 1,700 McVitie's [[Rich tea]] biscuits and {{Convert|17|kg|lb|abbr=on}} of chocolate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/europe/03/26/uk.royal.wedding.cake/index.html?hpt=C2|title=Prince William's Groom's Cake|publisher=cnn.com|accessdate=27 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, McVitie's announced their intention to make 157 shop floor roles redundant at their Manchester manufacturing facility.<ref>{{cite web|title=157 jobs could go at McVities|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/business/157-jobs-could-go-mcvities-7795155|website=Manchester Evening News|date=19 September 2014}}</ref> This redundancy announcement was also due to the modernisation agenda of the company and also involves a move from an 8-hour 5 day operation, to a 12-hour 7 day operation.\n\nIn November 2014, United Biscuits, and hence also McVitie's, became owned by Turkish company [[Y\u0131ld\u0131z Holding|Yildiz]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Jaffa Cakes and McVitie's maker sold to Turkish food group in \u00a32bn deal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/nov/03/united-biscuits-jaffa-cakes-mcvities-yildiz-two-billion-deal|newspaper=The Guardian|date=3 November 2014|last1=Wood|first1=Zoe}}</ref> which in 2016 grouped some of its subsidiaries including United Biscuits as [[pladis]] (see [[United Biscuits]]).\n\n==Product lines==\n\n===Biscuits===\n[[File:Biscuit tins VA 2490.JPG|thumb|A 19th century McVitie & Price's Digestive [[biscuit tin]], located in the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]], London]]\n*[[Digestive biscuit|Digestives]]\n*[[Fig Roll]]\n*[[Ginger Nuts]]\n*[[HobNobs|Hobnobs]]\n*[[Cookies]], including Boasters.\n*[[Rich tea|Rich Tea]]\n*[[Penguin (biscuit)|Penguin]]\n*[[Taxi (chocolate)|Taxi]]\n*Gold Bar\n*All Butter [[Shortbread]]\n*Fruit shortcake<ref>[http://www.mcvities.co.uk/products/fruit-shortcake \"McVitie's Fruit Shortcake\"]. McVitie's.</ref>\n*Tasties<ref>[http://www.thegrocer.co.uk/fmcg/ambient/cakes-and-biscuits/mcvities-launches-1-range-of-tasties-biscuits/235420.article \"McVitie's launches Tasties biscuits\"]. The Grocer.</ref>\n*[[BN Biscuit|BN]]\n*Deli Choc\n*[[Trio (chocolate bar)|Trio]]\n*United (discontinued)<ref>[http://www.dailyedge.ie/united-chocolate-bars-2593083-Feb2016/ \"United Bars are the eighties sweets we need to see back on our shelves,\" ''The Daily Edge'', 9 February 2016]</ref>\n*Club Biscuits\n\n===Cakes===\n*[[Tate & Lyle|Lyle's]] Golden Syrup Cake\n*Jamaica Ginger Cake\n*Lemon Cake\n*Mini Rolls\n* Waffles\n* [[Tunis Cake]]\n* [[Fruit cake]]\n* Iced Gems\n* [[Carrot Cake]]\n*[[Jaffa Cakes]]\n\n===Other snacks===\n[[File:McVities Mini Cheddars (Original and BBQ) with bags.jpg|thumb|right|Mini Cheddars (\"original\" and \"BBQ\" flavours)]]\n*[[Cheddars]]\n*[[Mini Cheddars]]\n*Krackawheats\n*Victoria Biscuit Selection\n*McVities Digestive Slices\n*Breakfast\n*Nibbles (Digestive and Hobnob varieties)\n*Digestive Thins\n*Cracker Crisps\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Food|United Kingdom}}\n*[[Burton's Foods]]\n*[[Fox's Biscuits]]\n*[[Jacob Fruitfield Food Group]]\n*[[Huntley & Palmers]]\n*[[Sunshine Biscuits (Australia)]], a licensed manufacturer of McVitie's biscuits\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|McVitie's}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20190624094737/http://www.unitedbiscuits.com/our-brands/mcvities/ United Biscuits - page on McVitie's.]\n*[http://www.mcvities.jp/ Official McVitie's site in Japan]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (in Japanese).\n\n{{Y\u0131ld\u0131z Holding}}\n\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Biscuits (British style)]]\n[[Category:Scottish brands]]\n[[Category:United Biscuits brands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 1830]]\n[[Category:1830 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:British Royal Warrant holders]]\n[[Category:Gorgie]]\n[[Category:History of Edinburgh]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = McVitie's\n| native_name      = <!-- Company's name in home country language -->\n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-2 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. If there is more than one native name, in different languages, enter those names using {{tl|lang}}, instead. -->\n| trading_name     = <!-- d/b/a/, doing business as - if different from legal name above -->\n| logo             = New McVitie's Logo.jpg\n| logo_size        = 220px\n| logo_caption     = The McVitie's logo as updated in 2005\n| image            = \n| image_caption    = \n| type             = Subsidiary\n| traded_as        = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| founder          = Richard McVitie\n| defunct          = <!-- {{End date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| fate             = \n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = \n| industry         = [[Confectionery]]\n| genre            = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies -->\n| products         = \n| production       = \n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| aum              = <!-- Only used with financial services companies -->\n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = [[pladis]]\n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = {{URL|www.mcvities.com}}\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n| romanized        = \n| former type      = \n| foundation       = [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]] ({{Start date|1830}})\n| location_city    = \n| location_country = [[United Kingdom]]\n| locations        = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices, etc. -->\n| bodystyle        = \n}}\n\n'''McVitie's''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] snack food brand owned by [[United Biscuits]]. The name derives from the original Scottish biscuit maker, McVitie & Price, Ltd., established in 1830 on Rose Street in [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]]. The company moved to various sites in the city before completing the St. Andrews Biscuit Works factory on Robertson Avenue in the [[Gorgie]] district in 1888.<ref name=\"archives\">{{Cite web|last=The National Archives of Scotland |authorlink=National Archives of Scotland |title=McVitie & Price, Ltd |url=http://www.dswebhosting.info/NAS/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Site20&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqSearch=(RefNo=='GD381/3') |accessdate=2 November 2007 |format=&ndash; <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=author%3AThe+National+Archives+of+Scotland+intitle%3AMcVitie+%26+Price%2C+Ltd&as_publication=&as_ylo=&as_yhi=&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup>  }}{{dead link|date=December 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The company also established one in Glasgow and two large manufacturing plants south of the border, in [[Heaton Chapel]], [[Stockport]], and [[Harlesden]], [[London]]. Under United Biscuits McVitie's holds a [[Royal Warrant of Appointment (United Kingdom)|Royal Warrant]] from Queen [[Elizabeth II]].\n\nThe best-selling [[biscuit]] manufacturer in the United Kingdom, McVitie's produces [[chocolate digestive]]s, [[Hobnob biscuit|Hobnobs]] and [[Rich tea]] (ranked the three favourite biscuits to [[Dunking (biscuit)|dunk]] into tea), and [[Jaffa Cakes]] (the best selling cake in the UK).\n\n==History==\n[[File:McVitie's Biscuit Factory, Wellington Road North, Stockport - geograph.org.uk - 803875.jpg|thumb|McVitie's factory in [[Manchester]] and [[Stockport]] which produces over 2,000 [[Jaffa Cakes]] a minute.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Jaffa Cakes - definitely not biscuits - prepare to take on imitators |last=Wallop |first=Harry |quote=The factory, which covers more than 10 acres, produces 2,000 Jaffa Cakes a minute |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=6 May 2012 }}</ref>]]\nRobert McVitie had two biscuit works at the head of [[Leith Walk]] in [[Edinburgh]] in 1870: 12 Antigua Street and 2 East London Street. McVitie lived nearby in a flat at 76 Broughton Street.<ref>Edinburgh Post Office Directory 1870</ref>\n\nThe established Edinburgh biscuit company of Robert McVitie was joined in 1875 by [[Charles Edward Price]] to create McVitie & Price. On the death of Robert senior, Robert McVitie junior joined and the firm expanded. In 1888 they built the huge St Andrews Biscuit Works on Robertson Avenue in the [[Gorgie]] district of south-west Edinburgh.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.mcvities.co.uk/about | title=McVitie's History &#124; McVitie's UK}}</ref>\n\nThough the original Gorgie factory burned down in 1894, it was rebuilt the same year and remained operative until 1969, when production ceased and operations were transferred to the English sites which had been established at [[Harlesden]] in 1910 and [[Manchester]] in 1917. The firm acquired the Edinburgh bakery of Simon Henderson & Sons in 1922.<ref name=\"archives\"/> McVitie & Price merged with another Scottish bakery company, Macfarlane, Lang & Co., Ltd, in 1948 to become United Biscuits Group.<ref>{{Cite web | last=United Biscuits| title=Our History| url=http://www.unitedbiscuits.com/802561A0047922E/vWeb/pcTSTT5DWHZ4| accessdate=6 November 2007 | format= &ndash; <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=author%3AUnited+Biscuits+intitle%3AOur+History&as_publication=&as_ylo=&as_yhi=&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup> | postscript=<!--None-->}} {{Dead link|date=March 2009}}</ref> McVitie's brand products are now manufactured in five United Kingdom factories: the two former McVitie & Price factories in Harlesden and Manchester, a former Macfarlane, Lang & Co. factory named Victoria Biscuit Works in [[Glasgow]], a former [[Carr's]] factory named The Biscuit Works established 1831 in [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]], and the McVitie's Cake Co. factory (formerly Riley's Toffee Works) in [[Halifax, West Yorkshire|Halifax]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.unitedbiscuits.com/80256C1A0047922E/vWeb/pcTSTT5DWHZ7| title=Our Locations| publisher=United Biscuits| accessdate=16 August 2007| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070624214113/http://www.unitedbiscuits.com/80256C1A0047922E/vWeb/pcTSTT5DWHZ7| archivedate = 24 June 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:McVitie's chocolate digestive biscuit.jpg|thumb|200px|left|McVitie's [[chocolate digestive]]. First produced in 1925, travel writer [[Bill Bryson]] called it a \u201cBritish masterpiece\u201d. It is the most popular biscuit in the UK to [[Dunking (biscuit)|dunk]] into tea.]]\n\nMcVitie & Price's first major biscuit was the McVitie's [[digestive biscuit|Digestive]], created in 1892 by a new young employee at the company named [[Sir Alexander Grant, 1st Baronet|Alexander Grant]].<ref name=\"McVities\"/> The biscuit was given its name because it was thought that its high baking soda content served as an aid to food digestion.<ref name=\"McVities\">[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2591803/McVities-Digestive-Hobnobs-shock-Weve-eating-wrong-way.html \"Crumbs, we've been eating McVitie's Digestives and Hobnobs all wrong! Firm says chocolate part is the BOTTOM\"]. ''Daily Mail'' (London). Retrieved 28 December 2014</ref> Grant was later to become managing director of the company. In 1923 he was the main benefactor in the establishing the [[National Library of Scotland]] giving an endowment of \u00a3100,000. Grant donated a further \u00a3100,000 in 1928 to assist with the building of the [[National Library of Scotland|National Library]] premises on [[George IV Bridge]] in Edinburgh.<ref>Macmillan, p.238-52</ref>\n\nIn 1924 Ramsay MacDonald, prime minister of Britain\u2019s new Labour Government, admitted that Grant had given him a Daimler car and \u00a330 000 of shares in the McVitie and Price company. Grant had been MacDonald\u2019s childhood friend, and shortly after received a baronetcy (hereditary knighthood) from the prime minister. The affair, regarded by many as corruption by the prime minister, severely shook the government.<ref>William D Rubinstein 'Twentieth-Century Britain: A Political History', Palgrave, 2003 p146.</ref>\n\nThe McVitie's Chocolate Homewheat Digestive was created in 1925. Over 71 million packets of McVitie's [[chocolate digestive]]s are eaten in the United Kingdom each year, equating to 52 biscuits per second.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.unitedbiscuits.com/80256C1A0047922E/vWeb/pcTSTT5EPGEC| title=McVitie's| publisher=United Biscuits| accessdate=16 August 2007| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070809043301/http://www.unitedbiscuits.com/80256C1A0047922E/vWeb/pcTSTT5EPGEC| archivedate = 9 August 2007}}</ref> [[HobNob]]s were launched in 1985 and a [[Types of chocolate|milk chocolate]] variant followed in 1987.<ref name=\"McVities\"/> Launched in 1927, [[Jaffa Cakes]]  were ranked the best selling cake or biscuit in the UK in 2012.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/9249366/Jaffa-Cakes-definitely-not-biscuits-prepare-to-take-on-imitators.html \"Jaffa Cakes - definitely not biscuits - prepare to take on imitators\"]. ''The Daily Telegraph'' (London). Retrieved 28 December 2014</ref>\n\nIn 1947, McVitie & Price made the wedding cake for [[Elizabeth II|Princess Elizabeth]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Philip Mountbatten]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7100546.stm| title=Sixty facts about a royal marriage (item 43)| publisher=BBC News| accessdate=15 January 2008 | date=18 November 2007}}</ref> Some of the products in the McVitie's line were rebranded ''McV'' in 2002, but this was replaced in 2005 with a restyled version of the ''McVitie's'' brand logo. In 2007, United Biscuits [[licensed]] the McVitie's brand to [[Meiji Seika|Meiji Seika Kaisha Ltd]] for biscuit production in [[Japan]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nicecupofteaandasitdown.com/biscuits/previous.php3?item=157| title=Japanese McVities Digestives| publisher=nicecupofteaandasitdown.com| accessdate=16 August 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:McVitie's HobNobs Nobbly Oaty Biscuits.jpg|thumb|right|McVitie's [[Hobnob biscuit|Hobnobs]] (plain). The chocolate version was named the UK's favourite biscuit in a 2014 poll.]]\nIn 2009, McVitie's biscuits were voted the most popular biscuits to [[Dunking (biscuit)|dunk]] in [[Tea in the United Kingdom|tea]], with McVitie's [[chocolate digestive]]s, [[Rich tea]] and [[Hobnobs]] ranked the country's top three favourite biscuits in 2009.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/foodanddrink/foodanddrinknews/4927255/Chocolate-digestive-is-nations-favourite-dunking-biscuit.html \"Chocolate digestive is nation's favourite dunking biscuit\"]. ''The Daily Telegraph'' (London). 2 May 2009</ref>\n\nIn March 2011, it was announced that [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|Prince William]] had chosen a [[groom's cake]] for his [[Wedding of Prince William and Catherine Middleton|wedding]] reception, made from 1,700 McVitie's [[Rich tea]] biscuits and {{Convert|17|kg|lb|abbr=on}} of chocolate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/europe/03/26/uk.royal.wedding.cake/index.html?hpt=C2|title=Prince William's Groom's Cake|publisher=cnn.com|accessdate=27 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, McVitie's announced their intention to make 157 shop floor roles redundant at their Manchester manufacturing facility.<ref>{{cite web|title=157 jobs could go at McVities|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/business/157-jobs-could-go-mcvities-7795155|website=Manchester Evening News|date=19 September 2014}}</ref> This redundancy announcement was also due to the modernisation agenda of the company and also involves a move from an 8-hour 5 day operation, to a 12-hour 7 day operation.\n\nIn November 2014, United Biscuits, and hence also McVitie's, became owned by Turkish company [[Y\u0131ld\u0131z Holding|Yildiz]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Jaffa Cakes and McVitie's maker sold to Turkish food group in \u00a32bn deal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/nov/03/united-biscuits-jaffa-cakes-mcvities-yildiz-two-billion-deal|newspaper=The Guardian|date=3 November 2014|last1=Wood|first1=Zoe}}</ref> which in 2016 grouped some of its subsidiaries including United Biscuits as [[pladis]] (see [[United Biscuits]]).\n\n==Product lines==\n\n===Biscuits===\n[[File:Biscuit tins VA 2490.JPG|thumb|A 19th century McVitie & Price's Digestive [[biscuit tin]], located in the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]], London]]\n*[[Digestive biscuit|Digestives]]\n*[[Fig Roll]]\n*[[Ginger Nuts]]\n*[[HobNobs|Hobnobs]]\n*[[Cookies]], including Boasters.\n*[[Rich tea|Rich Tea]]\n*[[Penguin (biscuit)|Penguin]]\n*[[Taxi (chocolate)|Taxi]]\n*Gold Bar\n*All Butter [[Shortbread]]\n*Fruit shortcake<ref>[http://www.mcvities.co.uk/products/fruit-shortcake \"McVitie's Fruit Shortcake\"]. McVitie's.</ref>\n*Tasties<ref>[http://www.thegrocer.co.uk/fmcg/ambient/cakes-and-biscuits/mcvities-launches-1-range-of-tasties-biscuits/235420.article \"McVitie's launches Tasties biscuits\"]. The Grocer.</ref>\n*[[BN Biscuit|BN]]\n*Deli Choc\n*[[Trio (chocolate bar)|Trio]]\n*United (discontinued)<ref>[http://www.dailyedge.ie/united-chocolate-bars-2593083-Feb2016/ \"United Bars are the eighties sweets we need to see back on our shelves,\" ''The Daily Edge'', 9 February 2016]</ref>\n*Club Biscuits\n\n===Cakes===\n*[[Tate & Lyle|Lyle's]] Golden Syrup Cake\n*Jamaica Ginger Cake\n*Lemon Cake\n*Mini Rolls\n* Waffles\n* [[Tunis Cake]]\n* [[Fruit cake]]\n* Iced Gems\n* [[Carrot Cake]]\n*[[Jaffa Cakes]]\n\n===Other snacks===\n[[File:McVities Mini Cheddars (Original and BBQ) with bags.jpg|thumb|right|Mini Cheddars (\"original\" and \"BBQ\" flavours)]]\n*[[Cheddars]]\n*[[Mini Cheddars]]\n*Krackawheats\n*Victoria Biscuit Selection\n*McVities Digestive Slices\n*Breakfast\n*Nibbles (Digestive and Hobnob varieties)\n*Digestive Thins\n*Cracker Crisps\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Food|United Kingdom}}\n*[[Burton's Foods]]\n*[[Fox's Biscuits]]\n*[[Jacob Fruitfield Food Group]]\n*[[Huntley & Palmers]]\n*[[Sunshine Biscuits (Australia)]], a licensed manufacturer of McVitie's biscuits\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|McVitie's}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20190624094737/http://www.unitedbiscuits.com/our-brands/mcvities/ United Biscuits - page on McVitie's.]\n*[http://www.mcvities.jp/ Official McVitie's site in Japan]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (in Japanese).\n\n{{Y\u0131ld\u0131z Holding}}\n\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Biscuits (British style)]]\n[[Category:Scottish brands]]\n[[Category:United Biscuits brands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 1830]]\n[[Category:1830 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:British Royal Warrant holders]]\n[[Category:Gorgie]]\n[[Category:History of Edinburgh]]\n", "name_user": "109.154.218.93", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/McVitie%27s"}
